    caption: [shows the interaction between DNA and three zinc fingers of a single polypeptide from the mouse regula- tory protein Zif268. Many eukaryotic DNA-binding proteins contain zinc fingers. The interaction of a single zinc finger with DNA is typically weak, and many DNA-binding proteins, like Zif268, have multiple zinc fingers that substantially enhance binding by interacting simultaneously with the DNA. One DNA-binding protein of the frog Xenopus has 37 zinc fingers. There are few known examples of the zinc finger motif in bacterial proteins. c28RegulationOfGeneExpression.indd Page 1163 19/10/12 9:17 AM user-F408 c28RegulationOfGeneExpression.indd Page 1163 19/10/12 9:17 AM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop 28.1 Principles of Gene Regulation 1163],
